What cars and how many of them frequent the same 6 parking spots from 8am to 11pm throught the week?

Which days of the week were the most crowded?

To investigate the occupancy of parking spots throughout the week, and if there was at least one that was free for an additional car (ideally my family should we get a new car), let us first look at the days which had the most cars parked. (only the days Tuesday to Friday were used as these were the additional data value points collected and combining it with the previous set of data would result in inaccurate comparison of the total number of cars that frequented each parking lot)

It appears that Thursday was the most crowded day, with a total of 27/36 (6*6) parking spots occupied throughout the day. On the other hand, Tuesday was the least crowded day with only 22/36 parking spots occupied. Now we know that even on the most crowded day (Thursday), there are still parking spots available throughout the day to park at. However, how does this change throughout the week?

How does the mean number of cars parked change throughout the week?

Interestingly, this plot now appears to show us that Friday seems to be the more popular day for parking rather than thursday when we look at the average number of parking spots occupied, instead (with the exception tha the full data set was now used). Friday seems to be the only day where an average of 6 parking spots had been occupied at a given time. Along with Sunday, it also seems to have the highest median of about 4.3 (4) parking spots occupied at a given time. So now we know that my family could probably park our new car in any of these parking spots on every day but Friday. But we cannot not park our car on Friday! So let us look deeper into this trend, now analysing how this relationship differs within the day itself.

How does the mean number of cars parked vary across the different hours of the day throughout the week?

Generally, we can observe that the most popular parking times are 8.00am, 9.00pm and 11.00pm. This is especially clear from the quadratic curve peaking at these times. We know that parking on every other day except Friday should not be a problem for us. So, let us focus on the data for Friday. Friday seems to be relatively crowded throughout the day, but we notice that for most of the day, there is still at least one parking spot vacant except at 11.00pm. This is quite a problem for us since we need that spot to park our car at 11.00pm. Who is parking in that spot at 11.00pm? We need to find out if this person is a regular or if they are just a visitor. We might be able to do so if we investigate the type of car parked in that spot, and if they have parked there before.

What type of cars park in the parking spots on Friday - do the same cars always park in these spots?

It appears that there are 6 different cars which parked in these parking spots on Friday. We observe that cars black - 09, grey - 11, blue - 56, red - 34 and white - 81 were parked in the morning on Friday, and then later at night the same cars were parked, but grey - 11 was not parked and instead black - 89 was parked. This is good news for us, regardless, as there does not seem to be a single time period which is fully occupied on Friday. However, just to be sure, we infer that black - 89 is the visitor and grey - 11 is the regular, and we cross-check this against data from other days to seee if these same cars appear.
